  <title>Week 8 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the determinants of the following matrices.  Show
        the steps of the algorithm clearly or give a clear reason for
        the determinant using some other properties. (12). 
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            -6 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
            3 \amp 4 \amp -2 \\
            5 \amp -1 \amp -1 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            \dfrac{1}{3} \amp 0 \amp \dfrac{-1}{3} \\
            \dfrac{4}{5} \amp \dfrac{-3}{5} \amp \dfrac{1}{2} \\
            \dfrac{-2}{3} \amp \dfrac{7}{2} \amp \dfrac{1}{2}
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 \amp 3125 \amp 67989 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 1037529\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 19 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
            1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Under what conditions for <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are the
        following matrices invertible? (12) 
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            0 \amp 1 \amp a \\
            0 \amp 2 \amp b \\
            3 \amp 1 \amp 1 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp a \amp b \\
            b \amp b \amp a 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a \amp ab \amp b \\
            ab \amp b \amp b \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Here is a definition that will be used in thie question: the
        sum of two <m>n \times n</m> matrices, <m>A + B</m>, is simply
        the sum in each entry of the matrices. Using this definition,
        if <m>\det A = 0</m> and <m>\det B = 0</m>, it is not
        necessarily true that <m>\det (A + B) = 0</m>. Find a
        counter-example to show why this isn't true. In terms of
        matrices as transformations, explay why <m>\det (AB) = \det A
        \det B</m> but <m>\det (A+B) \neq \det A + \det B</m>. (6) 
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
